WEBVTT

00:00.579 --> 00:02.312
<i>Previously on</i>
The Big Bang Theory...

00:02.314 --> 00:03.927
I guess I'm still wondering

00:03.929 --> 00:05.795
if Emily and I
are right for each other.

00:05.797 --> 00:08.164
Does this have to do with
that girl you had coffee with?

00:08.166 --> 00:11.167
You mean the strong, sexy angel
I can't stop thinking about?

00:11.169 --> 00:13.503
Who can say?

00:13.505 --> 00:16.639
I need to come up with
a big idea to make some money.

00:16.641 --> 00:18.608
There's no reason you can't.
That's easy for you to say.

00:18.610 --> 00:20.043
You and Sheldon already came up

00:20.045 --> 00:21.845
with your
superfluid helium model.

00:21.847 --> 00:23.046
That's just research.

00:23.048 --> 00:24.814
We're never going
to make any money from it.

00:24.816 --> 00:26.783
Forget helium--
the real superfluid

00:26.785 --> 00:29.018
is the fruit punch in this mug.

00:29.020 --> 00:33.122
It reminds me of my daddy's
secret “Don't Tell Mama” juice.

00:34.860 --> 00:36.025
Maybe that's an idea.

00:36.027 --> 00:38.761
Guidance systems
for drunk people.

00:38.763 --> 00:40.930
They have that,
it's called Uber.

00:42.467 --> 00:44.200
Hey, in your supercooled
helium experiments,

00:44.202 --> 00:46.636
did you create
quantum vortices?

00:46.638 --> 00:47.637
Yeah, why?

00:47.639 --> 00:49.072
Well, if you made
a guidance system,

00:49.074 --> 00:51.407
couldn't you use those vortices
as a gyroscope?

00:51.409 --> 00:53.843
Wow. Never thought about that.

00:53.845 --> 00:55.612
And, since it's
in a quantum state,

00:55.614 --> 00:57.113
it would maintain
an infinite persistence.

00:57.115 --> 00:58.281
Groundbreaking
revelations,

00:58.283 --> 00:59.849
tropical drinks.

00:59.851 --> 01:03.720
Tell me this isn't like the best
episode of <i>Sex and the City.</i>

01:10.362 --> 01:11.661
Okay, I gotta ask--

01:11.663 --> 01:13.429
why are you wearing
a bow tie?

01:13.431 --> 01:16.366
I've never applied
for a patent before.

01:16.368 --> 01:18.201
I wanted to make
a good impression.

01:18.203 --> 01:21.471
Oh. Is the impression that
your first name is Pee-Wee?

01:21.473 --> 01:23.640
(chuckling)

01:26.611 --> 01:29.212
Yeah, well, you're an engineer.

01:29.214 --> 01:30.813
End of joke, burn.

01:33.652 --> 01:34.884
Come on in, fellas.

01:34.886 --> 01:36.886
See, he's not wearing a tie.

01:36.888 --> 01:38.121
Well, he's
a patent attorney.

01:38.123 --> 01:39.989
Maybe his tie is pending.

01:41.159 --> 01:43.326
So, I've reviewed
your paperwork,

01:43.328 --> 01:45.628
and it seems like
we've got everything we need

01:45.630 --> 01:46.696
to file a patent

01:46.698 --> 01:48.731
for your infinite
persistence gyroscope.

01:48.733 --> 01:49.832
That's great!
Excellent.

01:49.834 --> 01:51.200
So what happens next?

01:51.202 --> 01:52.669
Well, the legal team
needs to review

01:52.671 --> 01:54.604
existing patents
to avoid overlap.

01:54.606 --> 01:56.105
Oh, I don't think
there will be.

01:56.107 --> 01:57.607
Yes, we did
our own search.

01:57.609 --> 02:00.910
That's nice, but I think ours
might be a bit more thorough.

02:00.912 --> 02:04.647
(chuckles):
Get a load of this guy.

02:04.649 --> 02:07.016
Can you imagine if we
make money with this?

02:07.018 --> 02:08.584
If we do,
I am splurging

02:08.586 --> 02:11.321
on the best sinus irrigator
money can buy.

02:12.857 --> 02:14.023
That old sad story--

02:14.025 --> 02:17.060
guy gets a little money,
goes straight up his nose.

02:17.062 --> 02:20.797
Just need you to review
and sign this document

02:20.799 --> 02:22.932
acknowledging that you
understand the university

02:22.934 --> 02:25.802
will own 75% of the patent.

02:26.905 --> 02:29.172
75%?

02:29.174 --> 02:30.306
That's outrageous.

02:30.308 --> 02:33.109
This is our idea
based on our research.

02:33.111 --> 02:36.279
How can you possibly justify
owning a majority share?

02:36.281 --> 02:37.747
It's university policy.

02:37.749 --> 02:40.016
I know when I'm beat.

02:40.018 --> 02:42.385
Hold on, hold on.
So the three of us

02:42.387 --> 02:45.888
do all the work
and only end up with 25%?

02:45.890 --> 02:47.857
Dr. Hofstadter, this university

02:47.859 --> 02:49.792
has been paying your salaries
for over ten years.

02:49.794 --> 02:52.495
Did you think we do that out
of the goodness of our hearts?

02:52.497 --> 02:56.299
Well, until you just said
that mean thing, kinda.

02:57.435 --> 02:59.469
And as far as
Mr. Wolowitz is concerned,

02:59.471 --> 03:02.705
I'm afraid as a federal employee
on loan from NASA,

03:02.707 --> 03:04.474
your name can be
on the patent,

03:04.476 --> 03:07.877
but you're not entitled
to an ownership share.

03:07.879 --> 03:10.146
Wait, so this can turn out to be

03:10.148 --> 03:13.316
a financial success,
and I get nothing?

03:13.318 --> 03:17.220
Well, sometimes
they give you a plaque.

03:17.222 --> 03:18.721
Well, that's not fair.

03:18.723 --> 03:20.790
We should all get plaques.

03:23.261 --> 03:24.927
Sorry, but we
can't sign this.

03:24.929 --> 03:26.596
Come on, let's go.

03:26.598 --> 03:28.531
Thank you for your time.

03:31.269 --> 03:33.703
Couple of questions
about the plaque...

03:34.773 --> 03:38.374
♪ Our whole universe
was in a hot, dense state ♪

03:38.376 --> 03:41.711
♪ Then nearly 14 billion years
ago expansion started... Wait! ♪

03:41.713 --> 03:43.346
♪ The Earth began to cool ♪

03:43.348 --> 03:45.882
♪ The autotrophs began to drool,
Neanderthals developed tools ♪

03:45.884 --> 03:48.551
♪ We built the Wall ♪
♪ <i>We built the pyramids</i> ♪

03:48.553 --> 03:51.220
♪ Math, Science, History,
unraveling the mystery ♪

03:51.222 --> 03:53.122
♪ That all started
with a big bang ♪

03:53.124 --> 03:55.091
♪ <i>Bang!</i> ♪

03:55.092 --> 03:59.092
